	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:39:58.214141+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is the comprehensive sector impact report for Alphabet/Google's Q4 2025 earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Alphabet/Google Q4 2025 — Sector Impact Report\n*Earnings reported February 4, 2026*\n\n---\n\n### 1. GOOGL Stock Price Reaction\n\n| Metric | Detail |\n|--------|--------|\n| **After-hours move (Feb 4)** | **-3% to -5%** |\n| **Driver of decline** | $175B–$185B 2026 capex guidance — nearly **2x the 2025 spend** |\n| **Street capex estimate** | ~$119.5B — actual guidance was **~55% above consensus** |\n| **Sentiment** | \"Beat-and-drop\" — strong fundamentals overshadowed by AI spending anxiety |\n\nDespite beating on EPS ($2.82 vs. $2.63 est.) and revenue ($113.83B vs. $111.43B est.), shares declined after hours because the $175B–$185B capex range stunned analysts and mirrored the same \"capex-vs-ROI\" trade that punished Microsoft after its earnings a week earlier. Notably, CEO Sundar Pichai told investors the planned spending \"still won't be enough\" given supply constraints — a signal of intensifying competition for AI infrastructure.\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-googl-q4-2025-earnings.html) | [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-google-ai-spending-supply-constraints/) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/alphabet-is-doubling-its-capital-expenditure-to-a-staggering-usd180-billion-in-2026-earnings-suggest-that-the-companys-ai-investments-may-be-paying-off)\n\n---\n\n### 2. Ad Tech Sector — Search & Programmatic\n\n#### Search (Google's Core Business)\n- **Google Search & Other:** $63.1B, **+17% YoY** — strong acceleration driven by AI-enhanced search features (AI Overviews monetization)\n- Search grew while **Google Network** fell -2% YoY to $7.83B — a structural signal that open-web programmatic display continues to lose share to walled gardens\n\n#### Market Concentration — The Big 3 Squeeze\nThe Google results confirmed the accelerating concentration of digital ad spend:\n- **Alphabet + Amazon + Meta** will collectively absorb the vast majority of incremental global ad spend between 2025 and 2027\n- The rest of the market — publishers, broadcasters, mid-tier ad tech players — competes for leftover marginal dollars as global ad growth runs at ~9%\n\n#### Impact on Meta, Snap, Pinterest\n\n| Platform | Status | Notable Development |\n|----------|--------|---------------------|\n| **Meta** | Benefiting | FY2025 ad revenue +22% to $196.2B; Q1 2026 guidance suggests acceleration. Competing directly with Google for incremental share |\n| **Snap** | Squeezed | Signed $400M Perplexity deal for AI-powered content; advertising weakness continues; revenue from deal expected in 2026 |\n| **Pinterest** | Stable-ish | Revenues projected to grow to $4.8B in 2026 from $3.65B in 2024; maintaining specialty niche in visual commerce advertising |\n\n**Key dynamic:** Google's search strength is *not* hurting Meta — both are winners as they drain spend away from smaller ad networks. Snap and the long tail of ad tech continue to be squeezed.\n\n**Sources:** [WARC](https://www.warc.com/content/feed/google-q4-fy-2025-strong-ad-growth-masks-investor-nerves-over-alphabets-ai-bill/en-GB/11311) | [Motley Fool on Meta](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/01/30/meta-platforms-do-the-unthinkable-to-google-in-202/) | [Investing.com — Pinterest SWOT](https://www.investing.com/news/swot-analysis/pinterests-swot-analysis-stock-faces-mixed-signals-amid-ad-tech-evolution-93CH-4361699)\n\n---\n\n### 3. YouTube — Streaming & Social Media Advertising Impact\n\n#### Q4 Performance\n- **YouTube Ads Q4 2025:** $11.38B (+8.7% YoY) — **missed** the $11.84B Street estimate\n- Miss attributed to: reduced post-election political advertising, tough comps from Q4 2024\n- **Full-Year 2025 YouTube Revenue (ads + subscriptions):** **>$60 billion** — crossing this threshold for the first time\n\n#### YouTube vs. Netflix — The Headline\nYouTube's $60B+ annual revenue in 2025 **surpassed Netflix's $45.18B** in full-year revenue, making YouTube effectively the world's largest video platform by revenue. Netflix co-CEO Ted Sarandos acknowledged the competitive shift directly:\n\n> *\"YouTube is not just user-generated content and cat videos anymore. They are TV. So we all compete with them in every dimension: for talent, for ad dollars, for subscription dollars, for all forms of content.\"*\n\n#### Advertising Market Implications\n- Netflix's ad tier generated ~$1.5B in 2025 ad revenue (>2.5x growth from 2024), targeting $3B in 2026 — but this remains a rounding error vs. YouTube\n- YouTube's combination of free (ad-supported) + subscription tiers is proving the dominant model for video monetization\n- YouTube Shorts continues to compete directly with TikTok and Instagram Reels for short-form social ad budgets\n\n**Sources:** [Variety](https://variety.com/2026/digital/news/youtube-2025-total-revenue-ads-subscriptions-alphabet-earnings-1236652260/) | [Design Rush](https://news.designrush.com/youtube-outearns-netflix-ads-subscriptions-2025-revenue) | [ALM Corp](https://almcorp.com/blog/youtube-largest-media-company-2025-surpasses-disney/)\n\n---\n\n### 4. Cloud Sector — GCP vs. Azure vs. AWS\n\n| Provider | Q4 2025 Growth | Revenue | Market Share |\n|----------|---------------|---------|-------------|\n| **GCP (Google)** | **+48% YoY** | **$17.66B** | **~14%** (up from ~12%) |\n| **Azure (Microsoft)** | +39% YoY | $32.9B (segment) | ~21% (up from ~20%) |\n| **AWS (Amazon)** | ~+17.5% YoY | ~$30.9B | ~28% (down from ~30%) |\n\nGCP's 48% growth was the **fastest among the Big Three** — a decisive quarter for Google Cloud's credibility as an enterprise platform. Key metrics:\n\n- **$240B backlog** (up 55% QoQ) — the demand signal is unprecedented\n- **$70B+ annual run rate** — firmly in AWS territory as a serious enterprise vendor\n- **8M+ Gemini Enterprise paid seats** across 2,800+ companies\n- Vertical integration (TPU chips + Gemini models + GCP platform) positions Google uniquely for AI-native workloads\n- **Gemini inference cost efficiencies** reported to be materially reducing cost-to-serve — improving margin outlook\n\n**Structural shift:** AWS's ~17.5% growth vs. GCP's 48% shows AI workloads are disproportionately flowing to Azure and GCP. AWS's lack of a native frontier AI model is increasingly a competitive liability.\n\n**Sources:** [Windows Forum Q4 Cloud Analysis](https://windowsforum.com/threads/q4-2025-cloud-ai-push-aws-azure-google-cloud-scale-and-margin.401419/) | [emma Cloud Market Share](https://www.emma.ms/blog/cloud-market-share-trends) | [SiliconAngle](https://siliconangle.com/2025/08/09/cloud-quarterly-azure-ai-pop-aws-supply-pinch-google-execution/)\n\n---\n\n### 5. AI & Semiconductor Impact — NVIDIA/AMD\n\n#### Alphabet's $175–185B Capex — A Windfall for Chip Suppliers\n- 2025 capex: ~$85–90B | 2026 guidance: **$175–185B** — nearly a doubling\n- Approximately **60% of capex goes to servers** (GPU/TPU purchases) and 40% to data centers and networking\n- Google disclosed it will be **among the first to deploy NVIDIA's Vera Rubin GPU platform** (announced at CES 2026)\n\n#### NVIDIA Impact\n- Alphabet's capex surge, combined with Meta's similar announcement, was characterized as \"great news for Nvidia stock investors\"\n- Wall Street consensus for Nvidia fiscal 2027 revenue growth is +52% — analysts noted the Alphabet/Meta capex figures make a beat of that target likely\n- Google's TPU development (custom silicon) does partially displace GPU purchases — but absolute scale means NVIDIA still benefits significantly\n\n#### AMD Position\n- Less directly called out, but AMD's GPU data center segment benefits from any broad infrastructure expansion\n- Google's multi-vendor chip strategy (TPUs for training + NVIDIA for inference) limits but doesn't eliminate AMD's opportunity\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware — Capex Analysis](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/alphabet-is-doubling-its-capital-expenditure-to-a-staggering-usd180-billion-in-2026-earnings-suggest-that-the-companys-ai-investments-may-be-paying-off) | [Motley Fool — NVIDIA Impact](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/02/05/alphabet-just-delivered-great-news-for-nvidia-stoc/) | [CMC Markets — Mag 7 Capex](https://www.cmcmarkets.com/en-gb/opto/magnificent-7-earnings-part-2-massive-ai-capex)\n\n---\n\n### 6. Antitrust & Regulatory Impact on Ad Tech Ecosystem\n\n#### DOJ Ad Tech Ruling (April 2025)\n- Federal Judge Leonie Brinkema ruled on **April 17, 2025** that Google held **illegal monopolies** in publisher ad servers and ad exchanges\n- Specific finding: Google unlawfully tied **DFP (publisher ad server) to AdX (ad exchange)**, coercing publishers into a captive ecosystem\n- European Commission separately fined Google **€2.95 billion** and ordered it to end abusive practices in programmatic ad-buying tools (September 2025)\n\n#### Remedies Phase — Ongoing at Q4 Earnings\nAt the time of Alphabet's Q4 2025 earnings (February 2026), the remedies decision was pending. Judge Brinkema had indicated her ruling would come in **January–February 2026**. Two competing proposals were on the table:\n\n| Party | Proposed Remedy |\n|-------|----------------|\n| **DOJ** | Force Google to **divest AdX** and open-source its auction technology |\n| **Google** | Behavioral remedies only — technical integrations to enhance publisher access, no structural breakup |\n\n#### Market Implications\n- A structural divestiture of AdX would be **the most significant ad tech market disruption in a decade** — opening the exchange market to independent competition\n- Ad tech beneficiaries if Google is forced to divest: The Trade Desk, Pubmatic, Magnite, Xandr (Microsoft)\n- Final enforceable outcome expected **2027–2028** after appeals\n- The ruling's ripple effect: A New York federal court in November 2025 applied broad preclusive effect, adopting the DOJ's findings — meaning other lawsuits against Google's ad tech practices now have a lower evidentiary bar\n\n**Sources:** [AdExchanger — 2025 Year in Review](https://www.adexchanger.com/antitrust/2025-the-year-google-lost-in-court-and-won-anyway/) | [Digiday — Remedies Explained](https://digiday.com/marketing/googles-ad-tech-antitrust-remedy-phase-explained-doj-wants-googles-offerings-and-where-the-judge-might-land/) | [Dataslayer — Antitrust Ruling Analysis](https://www.dataslayer.ai/blog/google-antitrust-ruling-2025-how-ad-tech-could-change-forever) | [DLA Piper — NY Court Ruling](https://www.dlapiper.com/en/insights/publications/2025/11/new-york-federal-court-applies-broad-preclusive-effect-and-adopts-dojs-google-ad-tech-ruling)\n\n---\n\n### Summary: Key Sector Narratives\n\n| Sector | Verdict | Key Signal |\n|--------|---------|------------|\n| **Search Ad Tech** | Bullish | +17% search growth; AI Overviews monetizing well |\n| **Programmatic/Open Web** | Bearish | Google Network -2% YoY; antitrust remedy pending |\n| **Meta/Social Ads** | Neutral-Positive | Google strength doesn't hurt Meta; both drain from smaller players |\n| **Snap/Pinterest** | Bearish | Squeezed by Big 3 concentration; pivoting to non-ad revenue |\n| **YouTube/Streaming** | Bullish | >$60B annual revenue; surpassed Netflix; missed Q4 ad estimate |\n| **Cloud (GCP)** | Very Bullish | 48% growth — fastest Big Three; 14% market share; $240B backlog |\n| **NVIDIA/Semiconductors** | Very Bullish | $175–185B capex; Vera Rubin deployment; GPU demand surge |\n| **Ad Tech Antitrust** | High Risk | DOJ divestiture remedy pending; could restructure open-web display market |" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "604f3879-035f-42d7-9c83-0a6e781adaef" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Here is the comprehensive sector impact report for Alphabet/Google's Q4 2025 earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Alphabet/Google Q4 2025 — Sector Impact Report\n*Earnings reported February 4, 2026*\n\n---\n\n### 1. GOOGL Stock Price Reaction\n\n| Metric | Detail |\n|--------|--------|\n| **After-hours move (Feb 4)** | **-3% to -5%** |\n| **Driver of decline** | $175B–$185B 2026 capex guidance — nearly **2x the 2025 spend** |\n| **Street capex estimate** | ~$119.5B — actual guidance was **~55% above consensus** |\n| **Sentiment** | \"Beat-and-drop\" — strong fundamentals overshadowed by AI spending anxiety |\n\nDespite beating on EPS ($2.82 vs. $2.63 est.) and revenue ($113.83B vs. $111.43B est.), shares declined after hours because the $175B–$185B capex range stunned analysts and mirrored the same \"capex-vs-ROI\" trade that punished Microsoft after its earnings a week earlier. Notably, CEO Sundar Pichai told investors the planned spending \"still won't be enough\" given supply constraints — a signal of intensifying competition for AI infrastructure.\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-googl-q4-2025-earnings.html) | [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-google-ai-spending-supply-constraints/) | [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/alphabet-is-doubling-its-capital-expenditure-to-a-staggering-usd180-billion-in-2026-earnings-suggest-that-the-companys-ai-investments-may-be-paying-off)\n\n---\n\n### 2. Ad Tech Sector — Search & Programmatic\n\n#### Search (Google's Core Business)\n- **Google Search & Other:** $63.1B, **+17% YoY** — strong acceleration driven by AI-enhanced search features (AI Overviews monetization)\n- Search grew while **Google Network** fell -2% YoY to $7.83B — a structural signal that open-web programmatic display continues to lose share to walled gardens\n\n#### Market Concentration — The Big 3 Squeeze\nThe Google results confirmed the accelerating concentration of digital ad spend:\n- **Alphabet + Amazon + Meta** will collectively absorb the vast majority of incremental global ad spend between 2025 and 2027\n- The rest of the market — publishers, broadcasters, mid-tier ad tech players — competes for leftover marginal dollars as global ad growth runs at ~9%\n\n#### Impact on Meta, Snap, Pinterest\n\n| Platform | Status | Notable Development |\n|----------|--------|---------------------|\n| **Meta** | Benefiting | FY2025 ad revenue +22% to $196.2B; Q1 2026 guidance suggests acceleration. Competing directly with Google for incremental share |\n| **Snap** | Squeezed | Signed $400M Perplexity deal for AI-powered content; advertising weakness continues; revenue from deal expected in 2026 |\n| **Pinterest** | Stable-ish | Revenues projected to grow to $4.8B in 2026 from $3.65B in 2024; maintaining specialty niche in visual commerce advertising |\n\n**Key dynamic:** Google's search strength is *not* hurting Meta — both are winners as they drain spend away from smaller ad networks. Snap and the long tail of ad tech continue to be squeezed.\n\n**Sources:** [WARC](https://www.warc.com/content/feed/google-q4-fy-2025-strong-ad-growth-masks-investor-nerves-over-alphabets-ai-bill/en-GB/11311) | [Motley Fool on Meta](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/01/30/meta-platforms-do-the-unthinkable-to-google-in-202/) | [Investing.com — Pinterest SWOT](https://www.investing.com/news/swot-analysis/pinterests-swot-analysis-stock-faces-mixed-signals-amid-ad-tech-evolution-93CH-4361699)\n\n---\n\n### 3. YouTube — Streaming & Social Media Advertising Impact\n\n#### Q4 Performance\n- **YouTube Ads Q4 2025:** $11.38B (+8.7% YoY) — **missed** the $11.84B Street estimate\n- Miss attributed to: reduced post-election political advertising, tough comps from Q4 2024\n- **Full-Year 2025 YouTube Revenue (ads + subscriptions):** **>$60 billion** — crossing this threshold for the first time\n\n#### YouTube vs. Netflix — The Headline\nYouTube's $60B+ annual revenue in 2025 **surpassed Netflix's $45.18B** in full-year revenue, making YouTube effectively the world's largest video platform by revenue. Netflix co-CEO Ted Sarandos acknowledged the competitive shift directly:\n\n> *\"YouTube is not just user-generated content and cat videos anymore. They are TV. So we all compete with them in every dimension: for talent, for ad dollars, for subscription dollars, for all forms of content.\"*\n\n#### Advertising Market Implications\n- Netflix's ad tier generated ~$1.5B in 2025 ad revenue (>2.5x growth from 2024), targeting $3B in 2026 — but this remains a rounding error vs. YouTube\n- YouTube's combination of free (ad-supported) + subscription tiers is proving the dominant model for video monetization\n- YouTube Shorts continues to compete directly with TikTok and Instagram Reels for short-form social ad budgets\n\n**Sources:** [Variety](https://variety.com/2026/digital/news/youtube-2025-total-revenue-ads-subscriptions-alphabet-earnings-1236652260/) | [Design Rush](https://news.designrush.com/youtube-outearns-netflix-ads-subscriptions-2025-revenue) | [ALM Corp](https://almcorp.com/blog/youtube-largest-media-company-2025-surpasses-disney/)\n\n---\n\n### 4. Cloud Sector — GCP vs. Azure vs. AWS\n\n| Provider | Q4 2025 Growth | Revenue | Market Share |\n|----------|---------------|---------|-------------|\n| **GCP (Google)** | **+48% YoY** | **$17.66B** | **~14%** (up from ~12%) |\n| **Azure (Microsoft)** | +39% YoY | $32.9B (segment) | ~21% (up from ~20%) |\n| **AWS (Amazon)** | ~+17.5% YoY | ~$30.9B | ~28% (down from ~30%) |\n\nGCP's 48% growth was the **fastest among the Big Three** — a decisive quarter for Google Cloud's credibility as an enterprise platform. Key metrics:\n\n- **$240B backlog** (up 55% QoQ) — the demand signal is unprecedented\n- **$70B+ annual run rate** — firmly in AWS territory as a serious enterprise vendor\n- **8M+ Gemini Enterprise paid seats** across 2,800+ companies\n- Vertical integration (TPU chips + Gemini models + GCP platform) positions Google uniquely for AI-native workloads\n- **Gemini inference cost efficiencies** reported to be materially reducing cost-to-serve — improving margin outlook\n\n**Structural shift:** AWS's ~17.5% growth vs. GCP's 48% shows AI workloads are disproportionately flowing to Azure and GCP. AWS's lack of a native frontier AI model is increasingly a competitive liability.\n\n**Sources:** [Windows Forum Q4 Cloud Analysis](https://windowsforum.com/threads/q4-2025-cloud-ai-push-aws-azure-google-cloud-scale-and-margin.401419/) | [emma Cloud Market Share](https://www.emma.ms/blog/cloud-market-share-trends) | [SiliconAngle](https://siliconangle.com/2025/08/09/cloud-quarterly-azure-ai-pop-aws-supply-pinch-google-execution/)\n\n---\n\n### 5. AI & Semiconductor Impact — NVIDIA/AMD\n\n#### Alphabet's $175–185B Capex — A Windfall for Chip Suppliers\n- 2025 capex: ~$85–90B | 2026 guidance: **$175–185B** — nearly a doubling\n- Approximately **60% of capex goes to servers** (GPU/TPU purchases) and 40% to data centers and networking\n- Google disclosed it will be **among the first to deploy NVIDIA's Vera Rubin GPU platform** (announced at CES 2026)\n\n#### NVIDIA Impact\n- Alphabet's capex surge, combined with Meta's similar announcement, was characterized as \"great news for Nvidia stock investors\"\n- Wall Street consensus for Nvidia fiscal 2027 revenue growth is +52% — analysts noted the Alphabet/Meta capex figures make a beat of that target likely\n- Google's TPU development (custom silicon) does partially displace GPU purchases — but absolute scale means NVIDIA still benefits significantly\n\n#### AMD Position\n- Less directly called out, but AMD's GPU data center segment benefits from any broad infrastructure expansion\n- Google's multi-vendor chip strategy (TPUs for training + NVIDIA for inference) limits but doesn't eliminate AMD's opportunity\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware — Capex Analysis](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/alphabet-is-doubling-its-capital-expenditure-to-a-staggering-usd180-billion-in-2026-earnings-suggest-that-the-companys-ai-investments-may-be-paying-off) | [Motley Fool — NVIDIA Impact](https://www.fool.com/investing/2026/02/05/alphabet-just-delivered-great-news-for-nvidia-stoc/) | [CMC Markets — Mag 7 Capex](https://www.cmcmarkets.com/en-gb/opto/magnificent-7-earnings-part-2-massive-ai-capex)\n\n---\n\n### 6. Antitrust & Regulatory Impact on Ad Tech Ecosystem\n\n#### DOJ Ad Tech Ruling (April 2025)\n- Federal Judge Leonie Brinkema ruled on **April 17, 2025** that Google held **illegal monopolies** in publisher ad servers and ad exchanges\n- Specific finding: Google unlawfully tied **DFP (publisher ad server) to AdX (ad exchange)**, coercing publishers into a captive ecosystem\n- European Commission separately fined Google **€2.95 billion** and ordered it to end abusive practices in programmatic ad-buying tools (September 2025)\n\n#### Remedies Phase — Ongoing at Q4 Earnings\nAt the time of Alphabet's Q4 2025 earnings (February 2026), the remedies decision was pending. Judge Brinkema had indicated her ruling would come in **January–February 2026**. Two competing proposals were on the table:\n\n| Party | Proposed Remedy |\n|-------|----------------|\n| **DOJ** | Force Google to **divest AdX** and open-source its auction technology |\n| **Google** | Behavioral remedies only — technical integrations to enhance publisher access, no structural breakup |\n\n#### Market Implications\n- A structural divestiture of AdX would be **the most significant ad tech market disruption in a decade** — opening the exchange market to independent competition\n- Ad tech beneficiaries if Google is forced to divest: The Trade Desk, Pubmatic, Magnite, Xandr (Microsoft)\n- Final enforceable outcome expected **2027–2028** after appeals\n- The ruling's ripple effect: A New York federal court in November 2025 applied broad preclusive effect, adopting the DOJ's findings — meaning other lawsuits against Google's ad tech practices now have a lower evidentiary bar\n\n**Sources:** [AdExchanger — 2025 Year in Review](https://www.adexchanger.com/antitrust/2025-the-year-google-lost-in-court-and-won-anyway/) | [Digiday — Remedies Explained](https://digiday.com/marketing/googles-ad-tech-antitrust-remedy-phase-explained-doj-wants-googles-offerings-and-where-the-judge-might-land/) | [Dataslayer — Antitrust Ruling Analysis](https://www.dataslayer.ai/blog/google-antitrust-ruling-2025-how-ad-tech-could-change-forever) | [DLA Piper — NY Court Ruling](https://www.dlapiper.com/en/insights/publications/2025/11/new-york-federal-court-applies-broad-preclusive-effect-and-adopts-dojs-google-ad-tech-ruling)\n\n---\n\n### Summary: Key Sector Narratives\n\n| Sector | Verdict | Key Signal |\n|--------|---------|------------|\n| **Search Ad Tech** | Bullish | +17% search growth; AI Overviews monetizing well |\n| **Programmatic/Open Web** | Bearish | Google Network -2% YoY; antitrust remedy pending |\n| **Meta/Social Ads** | Neutral-Positive | Google strength doesn't hurt Meta; both drain from smaller players |\n| **Snap/Pinterest** | Bearish | Squeezed by Big 3 concentration; pivoting to non-ad revenue |\n| **YouTube/Streaming** | Bullish | >$60B annual revenue; surpassed Netflix; missed Q4 ad estimate |\n| **Cloud (GCP)** | Very Bullish | 48% growth — fastest Big Three; 14% market share; $240B backlog |\n| **NVIDIA/Semiconductors** | Very Bullish | $175–185B capex; Vera Rubin deployment; GPU demand surge |\n| **Ad Tech Antitrust** | High Risk | DOJ divestiture remedy pending; could restructure open-web display market |" ;
